05057nam a22007695i 9781487583460DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191976onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875834607 a10.3138/97814875834602doi  a(DE-B1597)527825  a(OCoLC)1129185266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aBUS0680002bisacsh04a338/.097122200aBeyond Industrial Growth /ced. by Abraham Rotstein. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1976  a1 online resource (148 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tThe loss of the steady state -- tNew perspectives for economic policy -- tThe politics of the steady state -- tSocial progress in the world of tomorrow -- tPerennial man and the slowed machine -- t'The computer does not impose on us the ways it should be used' -- tCONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the winter of 1974-5 six eminent Canadians were invited to lecture at Massey College on topics related to a central concern of our time -- the ability of Canadian affluence to continue to expand as it has. This book contains their various responses. The contributions are aimed at the intelligent general public rather than at specialists, and they preach neither doom nor utopia. The first piece is by Senator Maurice Lamontagne, who states the case for 'Futures Canada' -- a study centre designed to generate ideas to help guide the country through the transition to a more stable economy. In succeeding papers, A.W. Johnson looks for a new kind of economic thought not locked into traditional free market economics, and Charles Taylor sketches the danger -- which he thinks can be avoided -- of centralized authoritarian politics emerging as a response to difficulties. The same democratic thrust is shown by Claude Castonguay who argues for putting more meaning back into work and politics through more participation and more regional (particularly Québécois) autonomy. Vivian Rakoff sees little future for Marcusian cults of sexual liberation, thinking that people retain deep-seated bonds other than sex that will see them through change and keep them human, while George Grant concludes with the dissection of the false freedom and morality of modern rational-technological man. This book responds to problems set in a global context: Canada cannot avoid the current world drama of changing attitudes, goals, and life-styles. We have to shape our communal role, agree on our wants and priorities, and know what we think and what we ought to do, if the Canadian fabric of life is somehow to survive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNatural resourceszCanada. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh1 aCastonguay, Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, A.W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamontagne, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRakoff, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRotstein, Abraham, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTaylor, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758346040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487583460423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487583460.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archiv